			9 replies to &ldquo;<span>Is Taxation Theft?</span>&rdquo;		</h2>

		<ol class="commentlist">
				<li class="comment even thread-even depth-1" id="li-comment-1862">
		<article id="comment-1862" class="comment">
			<header class="comment-meta comment-author vcard">
				<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/4ef866326ef1810be90f1c9f9286bb55?s=44&amp;d=identicon&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-44 photo' height='44' width='44' /><cite><b class="fn"><a href='http://www.twoplustwoequalsfour.org/' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Four</a></b> </cite><a href="http://elidourado.com/blog/is-taxation-theft/#comment-1862"><time datetime="2011-09-03T08:34:12+00:00">September 3, 2011 at 8:34 am</time></a>			</header><!-- .comment-meta -->

			
			<section class="comment-content comment">
				<p>&#8220;Rights&#8221; don&#8217;t exist separate from voluntary contracts that define &#8220;rights&#8221; as mutual obligations.</p>
<p>Land is not owned it is used. Land is not property since man did not and cannot create land. Property is that which man creates. There is no &#8220;right&#8221; to property. When you create property, you own it. Property is a fact. </p>
<p>Property not &#8220;enforced&#8221; it is defended. Aggression against property is met with defence &#8211; what sophists call &#8220;enforcement&#8221;. Did the sophist require &#8220;enforcement&#8221; of his argument, of his intellectual property, for others to voluntarily receive it and consider it? No.</p>
<p>Any argument against property is a performative contradiction since the one who argues requires the use of his body, his property, to make the argument.</p>
<p>The action axiom establishes property as a fact: One who acts necessarily uses himself, his property, to act. This cannot be refuted since refutation requires action. </p>
<p>If taxation is defined as the successful extraction of fees under duress and threat of force against one&#8217;s body or other property, then taxation is theft. That 99.9% of people may submit to force does not change the immorality of force. The existence of fees, fines, and imprisonments for not consenting presupposes a lack of voluntary consent.</p>
<p>Coercion is the initiation of force that violates the non-aggression principle and is justifiably met with defence. Defence is not force but a reaction to force. Consent cannot be forced. Force presupposes a lack of voluntary consent.</p>
<p>Wikipedia: Action Axiom<br />
Wikipedia: Non-Aggression Principle</p>
