			<header class="comment-meta comment-author vcard">
				<img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/3387898eb97e92f78889b2e3efba5486?s=44&amp;d=identicon&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-44 photo' height='44' width='44' /><cite><b class="fn">bro</b> </cite><a href="http://elidourado.com/blog/is-taxation-theft/#comment-1863"><time datetime="2011-09-03T09:30:17+00:00">September 3, 2011 at 9:30 am</time></a>			</header><!-- .comment-meta -->

			
			<section class="comment-content comment">
				<p>Who has the greatest legitimacy over a given property: The dude on welfare, or the person who but sweat and tear in the land?</p>
							</section><!-- .comment-content -->

			<div class="reply">
							</div><!-- .reply -->
		</article><!-- #comment-## -->
	</li><!-- #comment-## -->
	<li class="comment even thread-even depth-1" id="li-comment-1864">
		<article id="comment-1864" class="comment">
			<header class="comment-meta comment-author vcard">
				<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/cff7eb28ee7540fdbf2f31de536c1211?s=44&amp;d=identicon&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-44 photo' height='44' width='44' /><cite><b class="fn">Adam Ozimek</b> </cite><a href="http://elidourado.com/blog/is-taxation-theft/#comment-1864"><time datetime="2011-09-03T09:55:45+00:00">September 3, 2011 at 9:55 am</time></a>			</header><!-- .comment-meta -->

			
			<section class="comment-content comment">
				<p>Very interesting piece. I think many would regard &#8220;centralized coercion results in expansions and abuses of power&#8221; as a reason to favor centralization, since expansion of power is necessary for the provision of other public goods they see as justifiable. </p>
<p>I do agree that taxation should not be satisfying, and I think some people find it satisfying in the way they find it satisfying when a criminal is locked up for a serious crime. Correct me if I&#8217;m wrong, but expanding on your point about not being satisfied on shooting a prowler, I think you have different intuitions than most people on the satisfaction of &#8220;justice&#8221;.  I would agree in the shooting a prowler case that it is not satisfying, so lets take a case closer to the margin. Imagine if the prowler had been breaking into your house several times a month for years and you finally caught him. And imagine instead of being shot he was arrested. This would be satisfying to me, because the stopping of an ongoing crime is satisfying, and so while taking freedom is not satisfying, stopping and preventing crime makes the whole thing on net satisfying. Would it be satisfying to you? </p>
<p>I think many people find taxation satisfying because what the money will be used for makes the whole thing on net satisfying. Others I think unfortunately find the taking in-and-of itself satisfying because it is expressive to them of our willingness to &#8220;do the right thing&#8221;. In the same way, however, I&#8217;d find our removal of the minimum wage to be in-and-of-itself satisfying because it is expressive of our willingness to &#8220;do the right thing&#8221;. </p>
<p>But I&#8217;m also only 20% sure about anything I&#8217;ve written here.</p>
							</section><!-- .comment-content -->

			<div class="reply">
							</div><!-- .reply -->
		</article><!-- #comment-## -->
	</li><!-- #comment-## -->
	<li class="comment byuser comment-author-elidourado bypostauthor odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="li-comment-1865">
		<article id="comment-1865" class="comment">
			<header class="comment-meta comment-author vcard">
				<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/89e73bc0be13bb5a395a4140290ee177?s=44&amp;d=identicon&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-44 photo' height='44' width='44' /><cite><b class="fn"><a href='http://elidourado.com/' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Eli</a></b> <span>Post author</span></cite><a href="http://elidourado.com/blog/is-taxation-theft/#comment-1865"><time datetime="2011-09-03T12:18:44+00:00">September 3, 2011 at 12:18 pm</time></a>			</header><!-- .comment-meta -->

			
			<section class="comment-content comment">
				<p>Adam, yes, that&#8217;s right. In the case of a repeated prowler, I would be relieved and (I&#8217;m only human) possibly elated when he was arrested. In spite of my relief, there is something deeply sad about the fact that I had to resort to violence to get that relief. If the goal is, as Will says, &#8220;a peaceful society of mutual benefit,&#8221; then we should remember that the prowler is <em>alienated</em> from that society. That, to me, is something to mourn.</p>
							</section><!-- .comment-content -->

			<div class="reply">
							</div><!-- .reply -->
		</article><!-- #comment-## -->
	</li><!-- #comment-## -->
	<li class="comment even thread-even depth-1" id="li-comment-1870">
		<article id="comment-1870" class="comment">
			<header class="comment-meta comment-author vcard">
				<img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/f5b7238bc8f9ee1a1f201d687fe506c5?s=44&amp;d=identicon&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-44 photo' height='44' width='44' /><cite><b class="fn"><a href='http://anarchyofproduction.wordpress.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Michael Wiebe</a></b> </cite><a href="http://elidourado.com/blog/is-taxation-theft/#comment-1870"><time datetime="2011-09-04T13:05:11+00:00">September 4, 2011 at 1:05 pm</time></a>			</header><!-- .comment-meta -->

			
			<section class="comment-content comment">
				<p>Regarding finding coercion satisfying, check out Long&#8217;s essay &#8220;<a href="http://web.archive.org/web/20090301163549/http://libertariannation.org/a/n030l2.html" rel="nofollow">Thinking our Anger</a>.&#8221;</p>
							</section><!-- .comment-content -->

