	<li class="comment even thread-even depth-1" id="li-comment-1881">
		<article id="comment-1881" class="comment">
			<header class="comment-meta comment-author vcard">
				<img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/759077e5242dad0df02f38871888fe8b?s=44&amp;d=identicon&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-44 photo' height='44' width='44' /><cite><b class="fn">a leap at the wheel</b> </cite><a href="http://elidourado.com/blog/is-taxation-theft/#comment-1881"><time datetime="2011-09-06T14:53:24+00:00">September 6, 2011 at 2:53 pm</time></a>			</header><!-- .comment-meta -->

			
			<section class="comment-content comment">
				<p>Interesting post.  I like the &#8220;taxation is theft&#8221; line only for reminding people that government action always devolves into the barrel of a gun. This feature of government isn&#8217;t necessarily a bad thing, but it rephrases the proposition of government into what I consider to be a more balanced view.</p>
							</section><!-- .comment-content -->

			<div class="reply">
							</div><!-- .reply -->
		</article><!-- #comment-## -->
	</li><!-- #comment-## -->
	<li class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="li-comment-1882">
		<article id="comment-1882" class="comment">
			<header class="comment-meta comment-author vcard">
				<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/0372135dc8065b88e49ba789118dd931?s=44&amp;d=identicon&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-44 photo' height='44' width='44' /><cite><b class="fn">Jeff Johnson</b> </cite><a href="http://elidourado.com/blog/is-taxation-theft/#comment-1882"><time datetime="2011-09-07T18:42:15+00:00">September 7, 2011 at 6:42 pm</time></a>			</header><!-- .comment-meta -->

			
			<section class="comment-content comment">
				<p>Without taxation, how do we maintain a military to defend the nation, pay for courts and police to defend property and enforce contracts, or fund scientific research that does not have immediate commercial application?</p>
<p>The idea that every common service can be provided by private sector organizations, or funded by user fees, or funded by voluntary contributions seems obviously preposterous. If we fund the military with voluntary contributions, how do you deal with free-riders?</p>
<p>Most people reading this post are already free-riders benefiting from the awesome sacrifice made by low-paid US military personnel. How do you intend to cover your debts? I don&#8217;t see people lining up with their checkbooks. That is why, awful as it is, taxation seems to me a necessary evil.</p>
							</section><!-- .comment-content -->

			<div class="reply">
							</div><!-- .reply -->
